North Korea Says 'No Chance' for Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that further sanctions had heightened distrust in the United States and that there was no chance that North Korea would unilaterally disarm and give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the U.N. General Assembly that North Korea took “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and making a decision to halt the development of nuclear technology and weapons.
"However, we have not received a satisfactory response from the United States," he added.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we don’t have faith in our national security. Under such circumstances, there is no chance that we will be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" approach to denuclearization that would gradually lift sanctions against North Korea, his statement is significant because he has not rejected unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the incumbent U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea wants to officially end the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the United States has conditioned Pyongyang to give up its nuclear weapons before that.
Washington has also ignored calls to reduce tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that denuclearization be carried out first and increases pressure through sanctions to enforce its goal, and even opposes a ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just a misconception of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases mistrust."
Ri did not mention whether there were plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which the US president spoke about earlier this week at the United Nations.
But the minister noted that Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in had held as many as three meetings in the past five months, adding: "If the denuclearization had been sought by South Korea rather than the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a standstill."
In any event, the tone of Mr. Ri’s speech was vastly different from last year when he spoke before the UN General Assembly and said that targeting the continental United States with missiles was inevitable after evil President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened North Korea’s “total destruction” last year at the United Nations, praised Kim for his courage to disarm, but added that there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
Trump said on Wednesday there was no timeline for denuclearization, adding: “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia have expressed the view that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must be strictly continued until there is complete, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea in 2006 in a bid to stop funding Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri at the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second meeting.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, but North Korea called him "gangster demands" after a few hours.
North Korea has agreed to meet with Moon this month to dismantle the missile site and nuclear complex that will take place if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He added that Kim had revealed to him that the “appropriate measures” were related to the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and certain steps toward stabilizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course to learn how to rest well
A new course at Harvard University has allowed all students to get a good night’s sleep in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of caffeine- and sleepless night-time learning.
The academic found that students at the world’s best university often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has devised a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
The idea for the course came after he gave a speech on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said, “Why did I only find out this now, in my final year of college?”
She said no one told her how important sleep was, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help academic and sporting success and generally improve health.
Professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health service, Paul Barreira, said the university decided to introduce the course after students were noticed a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks includes a picture of a dormitory where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how lack of sleep affects success, and how important sleep routines are.
During the lecture, students also learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
After that, a map of the campus with interactive icons is displayed that encourages students to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health,” Czeisler added.
A culture of pride in all-night learning before exams still exists, the professor says, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is an increasing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality sleep. Sleep also helps in the fight against obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, puts it into a state of starvation and provokes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemistry and biology from California, helped Professor Czeisler come up with a course after attending his first year of Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend the course to the entire campus.
As the next step, it plans to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar study course before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking up. They must be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
