And now the page from our Almanach on Sunday Morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years and a few days ago...the birth day of the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, and from this invention later developed a device known as the Geiger counter.
Geiger's counter has also become a major pillar of pop culture, for example in the 1950 film Bells of Colorado, in which the seemingly amazing scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans starred:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, and it's used to detect radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the atoms reacting to the radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: "Look at that, you can hear it!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name still lives on.
