HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has reported a 14% increase in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
Health officials say more than 820,000 people in the country have been infected.
About 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases have been transmitted through sex, a change from the past.
In the past, HIV was rapidly transmitted throughout parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
At a conference in Yunnan province, Chinese health authorities said that people who become infected with HIV in this way are almost gone.
However, every year the number of people living with HIV and AIDS increases by 100,000 people.
HIV transmission through sex is a persistent problem among the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be high.
Research estimates that because of conservative values in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with other men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of transmission of the disease in such relationships occur due to inadequate protection during sex.
As part of efforts to tackle the problem, the Chinese government promised free access to HIV medicines in 2003.
